# The 17 Principles of Design — Theoretical Foundation for Visual Composition

> These are the foundational principles that underpin EVERY visual decision.
> The other modules in this Design Bible are practical implementations of these principles.
> Before creating or evaluating any composition, internalize these — they are the WHY behind the rules.
>
> Sources: "Universal Principles of Design" (Lidwell, Holden & Butler),
> "Refactoring UI" (Wathan & Schoger), "Design Elements" (Timothy Samara),
> Toptal, Figma Resource Library, NN/g, Medium/Bootcamp.

---

## HOW ELEMENTS AND PRINCIPLES RELATE

**Elements** are the raw materials (line, shape, color, texture, space, value, form).
**Principles** are the rules for arranging those materials into effective compositions.

```
ELEMENTS (what you use)          PRINCIPLES (how you arrange them)
─────────────────────            ─────────────────────────────────
Line                             Hierarchy
Shape / Form                     Balance
Color                            Contrast
Texture                          Emphasis
Space                            Proportion & Scale
Value (light/dark)               Unity & Variety
                                 Rhythm, Repetition & Pattern
                                 Movement
                                 White Space
                                 Lines, Shapes, Texture (as compositional tools)
```

A principle without an element is abstract theory.
An element without a principle is visual noise.

---

## 1. HIERARCHY

**Definition**: The deliberate arrangement of elements to signal their order of importance, guiding the viewer from most to least critical.

**Why it matters in UI**: Users scan — they don't read. If everything has equal visual weight, nothing communicates. Hierarchy ensures the primary action, the key information, and the navigation path are unmistakable.

### PRACTICAL RULES:
- Establish **3 levels** minimum: primary (what they see first), secondary (supporting info), tertiary (metadata/actions)
- Use **size, weight, color, and position** together — not just one
- The most important element gets the most visual contrast against its surroundings
- In a screen, the eye should land on the **primary element within 1 second**
- Test: squint at the screen — what you see first IS your hierarchy (whether intended or not)

### COMMON MISTAKE:
```
WRONG: All text same size, same weight, same color
       → User scans randomly, misses the primary action

RIGHT: Title 28px Bold, body 16px Regular, caption 12px Gray
       → Eye flows: title → body → caption
```

**See also**: 00-core-principles (4 Pillars), 04-typography (type scale)

