## 6. SCALE

**Definition**: The size of elements relative to each other and to the composition as a whole. Scale creates visual importance and a sense of depth.

**Why it matters in UI**: Scale is the most immediate way to establish hierarchy. Users instinctively assign more importance to larger elements. Strategic scale differences guide the eye.

### PRACTICAL RULES:
- Use scale to establish **at least 3 distinct size levels** in any composition
- Hero/display text should be 2-3x larger than body text
- Primary cards can be larger than secondary cards to signal priority
- Scale down less important elements rather than scaling up important ones (prevents bloat)
- On mobile, scale is compressed — maintain relative proportions even as absolute sizes decrease
- Never let scale distort element integrity (e.g., stretching an image non-proportionally)

### COMMON MISTAKE:
```
WRONG: All cards same size in a dashboard where one metric is critical
       → The critical metric is lost among equals

RIGHT: Feature card at 2x width, secondary cards at 1x
       → Scale communicates: "THIS metric matters most"
```

**See also**: 03-layout-spacing (responsive), 18-responsiveness-constraints

