## 7. UNITY

**Definition**: The sense that all elements in a composition belong to the same system and work toward a common purpose. The whole feels intentional, not assembled from random parts.

**Why it matters in UI**: Unity = trust. When elements feel disconnected (different styles, inconsistent spacing, mixed metaphors), users perceive the product as unpolished or unreliable.

### PRACTICAL RULES:
- Use a **consistent color palette** across all screens (max 1 accent + neutrals + semantic)
- One typeface family (or two at most with clear roles)
- Same border-radius across all components (e.g., 8px everywhere, or 12px everywhere — not mixed)
- Same shadow style for all elevated elements
- Same icon style (don't mix outline and filled icons in the same context)
- Same spacing scale used globally (8px grid)
- A design system IS the implementation of unity

### COMMON MISTAKE:
```
WRONG: Card A has 8px radius, Card B has 16px radius, Button has 24px radius
       → Three different visual languages on one screen

RIGHT: All containers 12px radius, all buttons 8px radius (smaller for inline)
       → Consistent visual language
```

**See also**: 02-gestalt (similarity), 05-colors (palette), 20-design-judgment

