## 8. VARIETY

**Definition**: Intentional differences between elements that create visual interest and prevent monotony. Variety is the counterbalance to unity.

**Why it matters in UI**: Too much uniformity is boring and hard to scan — if everything looks the same, nothing has priority. Variety creates visual landmarks that help users navigate.

### PRACTICAL RULES:
- Vary **within the system** — different card types (horizontal, vertical, featured) using the same components
- Alternate section backgrounds (light → dark → light) to create visual rhythm
- Use imagery, illustration, or icons to break up text-heavy sections
- Vary content block heights to avoid a monotonous grid
- Variety should serve hierarchy — larger/different = more important, not just "different for fun"
- **Too much variety = chaos**. Limit variations to 2-3 per element type

### COMMON MISTAKE:
```
WRONG: Every section has the same layout — hero, 3 cards, CTA, repeat
       → User stops paying attention after the second section

RIGHT: Hero → 3 cards → testimonial (different layout) → 2-col feature → CTA
       → Each section feels fresh but cohesive
```

**See also**: 20-design-judgment (varying layouts), 16-anti-patterns (generic AI slop)

