## 10. REPETITION

**Definition**: The deliberate reuse of visual elements (colors, shapes, textures, fonts, spacing) to create consistency and reinforce relationships.

**Why it matters in UI**: Repetition trains users. When a blue button always means "primary action," users learn the pattern and navigate faster. Repetition IS learnability.

### PRACTICAL RULES:
- **All primary buttons** must look identical (same color, radius, height, font weight)
- **All headings at the same level** must use the same type treatment
- **All cards** in a list must share the same structure (image size, padding, text hierarchy)
- Navigation patterns repeat across all screens (same position, same style)
- If you introduce a visual element once, either repeat it or remove it — a one-off feels accidental
- Repetition + small variation = rhythm (see Principle 9)

### COMMON MISTAKE:
```
WRONG: Primary button on Screen A is rounded, on Screen B is square
       → User has to re-learn the interface on every screen

RIGHT: Primary button is ALWAYS 48px height, 8px radius, filled accent color
       → User knows what to expect
```

**See also**: 02-gestalt (similarity), 06-buttons-cta (button consistency)

