## 11. PATTERN

**Definition**: The intentional repetition of multiple design elements working together to form a recognizable visual system. Patterns are repetition at a higher level of complexity.

**Why it matters in UI**: UI patterns are the learned conventions users bring from other apps. Following established patterns (top nav, bottom tabs, pull-to-refresh) reduces cognitive load. Breaking them creates friction.

### PRACTICAL RULES:
- Follow **platform conventions**: bottom tab bar on mobile, top nav on web, sidebar on desktop apps
- Card patterns: thumbnail + title + description + action is a learned pattern — don't reinvent without reason
- Form patterns: label above input, error below, submit at bottom — users expect this
- List patterns: consistent row height, left-aligned content, right-aligned metadata/chevron
- When you MUST break a pattern, make the new pattern learnable within one interaction
- Document your patterns in a design system — patterns only work when they're consistent

### COMMON MISTAKE:
```
WRONG: Settings uses a list pattern, but some items are cards, some are toggles
       inline, some are full-width buttons → No recognizable pattern

RIGHT: All settings items use the same row pattern (label + control right-aligned)
       → Scannable, predictable, fast
```

**See also**: 08-navigation (nav patterns), 09-cards-lists (card/list patterns), 01-ux-laws (Jakob's Law)

