## 13. WHITE SPACE (Negative Space)

**Definition**: The empty or unmarked areas in a composition — between elements, around elements, and within elements. White space is not wasted space; it is an active compositional tool.

**Why it matters in UI**: White space controls density, improves readability, creates breathing room, and signals importance. Premium apps feel premium largely because of generous white space.

### PRACTICAL RULES:
- **More white space around an element = more perceived importance**
- Content should fill no more than 60-70% of the viewport — the remaining 30-40% is breathing room
- Padding inside cards: at least 16px (preferably 24px)
- Section separators: use white space (32-48px gap) instead of explicit divider lines when possible
- Don't fear empty space — **fear cramped space**
- White space does NOT mean literally white — it means "unused by content" (can be any background color)
- The luxury brands test: Apple, Linear, Stripe all use generous white space as a design strategy

### COMMON MISTAKE:
```
WRONG: Every pixel filled with content, cards touching each other, no padding
       → Feels cheap, overwhelming, hard to scan

RIGHT: Generous padding, clear gaps between sections, content island in a sea of space
       → Feels premium, focused, easy to scan
```

**See also**: 03-layout-spacing (spacing scale), 20-design-judgment (Lesson 4: whitespace)

