## 14. COLOR (as Compositional Principle)

**Definition**: The strategic use of hue, saturation, and value to create mood, guide attention, communicate meaning, and establish visual hierarchy within a composition.

**Why it matters in UI**: Color is the fastest-processing visual property. Users register color before shape, size, or text. Used well, it clarifies. Used poorly, it creates noise.

### PRACTICAL RULES:
- **60-30-10 rule**: 60% dominant color (usually neutral), 30% secondary, 10% accent
- Accent color = primary action color. Use it for CTAs, active states, links — and almost nothing else
- Limit non-neutral colors to **2 maximum** on any screen (accent + one status)
- Color for meaning: red = error/destructive, green = success, yellow/orange = warning, blue = info
- Don't use semantic colors for decoration (no green text just because "green = positive vibes")
- Dark mode: reduce saturation and brightness; never invert pure black/white
- Color creates grouping: same-colored elements are perceived as related (Gestalt similarity)

### COMMON MISTAKE:
```
WRONG: 5 different accent colors on one screen — blue buttons, green labels,
       orange badges, purple links, red icons → Color soup

RIGHT: Blue accent for ALL interactive elements, gray for content, red only for errors
       → Color communicates function, not decoration
```

**See also**: 05-colors (full color system), 13-accessibility (contrast), 20-design-judgment (Lesson 1)

