## HOW PRINCIPLES INTERACT

No principle works alone. The power is in their interaction:

| Principle A | + Principle B | = Result |
|---|---|---|
| **Contrast** | + **Emphasis** | High contrast creates the focal point |
| **Repetition** | + **Unity** | Repeated elements unify the composition |
| **Variety** | + **Rhythm** | Varied elements with consistent spacing create flow |
| **Scale** | + **Hierarchy** | Larger elements are perceived as more important |
| **White space** | + **Emphasis** | Isolation through space draws attention |
| **Balance** | + **Movement** | Balanced weight still guides the eye directionally |
| **Color** | + **Contrast** | Color difference is the primary contrast mechanism |
| **Lines** | + **Movement** | Lines direct the eye path through the composition |
| **Shapes** | + **Unity** | Consistent shape language unifies visual identity |
| **Pattern** | + **Repetition** | Patterns are systems of repeated elements |
| **Proportion** | + **Balance** | Proportional elements feel balanced naturally |
| **Texture** | + **Variety** | Texture adds richness without structural variety |
| **Rhythm** | + **Movement** | Rhythmic spacing creates directional flow |

